                            <comment id="70837" author="mikee2185" created="Wed, 28 Sep 2011 08:19:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Since PUT returning an inserted object back is also perfectly valid scenario in REST, Spring should allow that.&lt;br/&gt;
Workaround is of course calling execute method manually, but I dont see reason not to include those few convenient methods into interface itself.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="71307" author="desmethans" created="Fri, 14 Oct 2011 06:59:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;a deleteForEntity and PostForEntity would also be useful:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul class=&quot;alternate&quot; type=&quot;square&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;when you do a DELETE request, you may receive a response with a body which contains information why the request has been refused. You want to read this body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;when you do a POST request, you may receive a response with a body which contains information why the request has been refused. You want to read this body.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="71309" author="mikee2185" created="Fri, 14 Oct 2011 07:02:27 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;postForEntity and similar are there. Delete not, but since it should be for generic use, they can be handy sometimes as well.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
